    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1904-01-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1904-01-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="912"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d912">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Finch</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Montevideo, Uruguay</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1904-01-13">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 13, 1904</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 713.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: No formal declaration of war has been published
                    by the Government of Uruguay or the Blanco party. Restrictive orders have been
                    issued, however, by the former. Egress from Montevideo and other points of the
                    Republic is restricted to foreigners, and they, before being allowed to depart,
                    are compelled to obtain permits issued only on certificates of nationality from
                    their respective consuls or ministers. A rigid press censorship has been
                    adopted. The telegraph companies of the Republic have been “intervened,” and the
                    circulation of outside newspapers containing prohibited matter—that is, news
                    matter relating to current events—forbidden.</p>
                <p>No order has as yet been published “intervening” the general mails.</p>
                <p>All Blanco clubs have been officially closed, and their presidents notified that
                    Blancos in larger numbers than two or three are not allowed to meet. To make
                    this order effective policemen guard the entrances to the regular meeting places
                    of Blancos.</p>
                <p>You will see by the above that while martial law has not been formally
                    proclaimed, martial law is being enforced throughout Uruguay.</p>
                <p>Respectfully,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William R. Finch.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
